name: Miner’s Lettuce
description: Rosette-forming plant, growing to a maximum of 40cm in height, the small pink orwhite flowershave five petals which grow at the end of the stems. It is common in the spring, and it prefers cool, damp conditions. It first appears in sunlit areas after the first heavy rains. Though, the best stands are found in shaded areas, especially in the uplands, into the early summer. As the days get hotter, the leaves turn a deep red color as they dry out.
location: along the path that leads down to the lower parking lot; Wild Places hike; near stair for climbing wall.
coolFact: The common name miner's lettuce refers to its use by California Gold Rush miners who ate it to get their vitamin C to prevent scurvy.Mild tasting leaves are not unlike spinach in texture

name: Shooting Star
description: The common shooting star plant is native to North American valleys and mountains. The plant may be found growing wild in low elevation areas in spring or in summer where consistent moisture is available.The plant forms rosettes of long narrow leaves and singular slender stems. The flowers hang in umbels from the stems and are white to bright pink
location: some on Cresta Blanca, upper Wild Places hike (near Buckeye trees)
coolFact: Shooting star plants are short-lived perennials, which do not produce flowers the first year.Common shooting star plants need protection from deer and elk, who dine on the early shoots in spring.The five lobes of the corolla (the structure formed by the petals) are turned backward, and the flowers point downward

name: Goldenback Fern
description: Small fern native to Western North America, including California.It is commonly found in mixed evergreen and oak forests, occasionally on dry brushy slopes, and prefers shaded areas.  Leaves are light green and have yellowish powder on the undersides. The spores follow the course of the veins on the underside of the leaf.
location: on the hillside along the middle Wild Places trail (near where it intersects with the low trail)
coolFact: Ferns are vascular plants that do not have seeds or flowers.Also called “Tattoo Fern”, if the leaf back is pressed onto the skin, the yellow powder will stick there and stay for quite some time. Remembernot to over pick the ferns.
